title: circle_cut
body:
For danbooru purposes a [b]circle cut[/b] (サークルカット) is a special type of advertisement for a doujin circle. There are two basic types pictures tagged as circle cut. The traditional variety has some distinct features:

* There is always a white box with a black border in the upper left corner.
* The circle name is displayed prominently on the cut, as well as textual information about what the circle intends to offer.
* They are (usually) in some standardized size, as specified by the event.
* They are [[monochrome]] for the printed event catalog, however the circle cuts are usually in color for web catalogs.

The box is there for specific information, such as when the doujin circle will be attending an event and where their stand exactly is. The box is also used by event goers as a checkbox, often with a highlighter.

The second kind of picture doesn't need to conform to the visual template exactly, but is characterized by having been released as a direct preparation of the exposition in question. They might vary in appearance from just a character's portrait + circle name, up to entire small scenes or comics whose purpose is to announce the booth number. For example, see post #634255 and post #161515.

title: philippe_(identity_v)
body:
Philippe, also known as [b]Wax Artist[/b], is a playable Hunter in [[Identity V]]. He was a talented wax artist and physiognomist with a fervent desire to rid the world of evil-doers before they could even commit crime. His theories and research brought him success, but also earned him the hatred of those who were judged because of him, and it resulted in the death of his beloved sister. Out of grief, Phillipe threw himself into his art and began to create even more lifelike statues, made in the appearance of criminals.

title: orpheus_(identity_v)
body:
Orpheus is a character in [[Identity V]] with three identities: the non-playable character "The Detective" and his younger selves - the playable Survivor "The Novelist" and [spoilers]Hunter "[[Nightmare (identity v)|]]" ([i]who isn’t included in this tag[/i])[/spoilers].

As "The Detective", Orpheus is the starting character of the Identity V story introduced in the Tutorial. He was a famous crime novelist, but lost his memory 10 years ago after a fire and became an unsuccessful private detective who then came to the mysterious Oletus Manor on the heels of a missing child case. The story is revealed through Orpheus' ability to deduce the personality and experiences of the characters through their diaries.
Detective Orpheus is a middle-aged man with [[short hair|short]] [[brown hair]] that is [[hair slicked back|combed back]] and [[brown eyes]]. He wears a [[white shirt|white]] [[collared shirt]], [[green vest]], [[red necktie]], [[brown coat|brown]] [[trench coat]], [[black pants]] and [[black footwear|black]] [[shoes]].

"The Novelist" is Orpheus before he lost his memory - a renowned novelist whose past is a mystery to all, even to himself. His main ability is to [[body switch|swap the control of characters]] with either his teammates or the Hunter for a set period of time.
Novelist Orpheus’ physical appearance is similar to Detective Orpheus, except much [[aged down|younger]] and with [[button eyes]] as he is a Survivor. His default outfit includes a [[white shirt|white]] [[collared shirt]], [[green ascot]], [[grey vest]], [[white coat]], [[white pants]], [[black footwear|black]] [[dress shoes]], and a [[monocle]]. He usually holds a [[book]] and a [[nib pen (object)|]].

title: douda_akaruku_nattarou
body:
[i]"Dou da, akaruku nattarou"[/i] ("There, that's brighter, isn't it?") is a dialog caption from a satirical cartoon from about 1928.

While the man in the cartoon is unnamed, he's apparently modeled after "Tadasaburō Yamamoto":https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/山本唯三郎, a businessman from humble roots who grew very successful in the late 19th/early 20th century.  He was known for flaunting his enormous wealth.  

One night, Yamamoto was leaving after an extravagant meal at a restaurant in Hakodate, when he saw a geisha searching around in the foyer for her shoes, having trouble because of the darkness.  He therefore pulled out a ¥100 bill (now worth about ¥1 million, allowing for inflation) and lit it to brighten the area.  The incident became famous as an anecdote of [i]nouveau riche[/i] behavior.

Years later, an artist named Kunibo Wada heard of the incident and drew a satirical cartoon depicting the situation, entitled ""The Age of Nouveau Riche Splendor":[https://kyuman.art/themes/main/facility/images/img_works_10.jpg]".  The cartoon appears in current Japanese history textbooks and so has some slight fame among the public.  It had gained a similar level of popularity as a motif for ASCII art and gag images.

title: renaissance
body: Generally known as "The Renaissance". title: karmatron_y_los_transformables
body:
[i][B]Karmatrón y los Transformables[/B][/i] ([I] "Karmatron and the Transformers":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karmatron [/I]) is a Mexican [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]] comic book created by [[Oscar Gonzalez Loyo]], and published first by CEPSA in 1986. 

The weekly series was published only in [[Mexico]], non-stop for 5 years, from 1986 to 1991 (until #298). 

The story deals with a group of brave variable geometry [[alien]] robots called the [i]Transformables[/i] (also known as the [i]Stellar Warriors[/i]) who help the powerful titular hero of the series, [i]Karmatron[/i] (a giant super robot), battle evil forces across the universe.

The series is notable because it's considered one of the first Mexican sci-fi [[super robot]] and [[mecha]] "[[comic]]", and because of its once-per-week publication schedule, an uncommon practice at its time of release.

It is fondly remembered by many Mexicans for its unique art style and its diverse and colorful characters, all influenced by American sci-fi and fantasy works (like [[Star Wars]], [[Battlestar Galactica]] and [[Transformers]]) as well as Japanese super robot and mecha anime shows from the 70s and 80s ([[Mazinger Z]] and [[Robotech]]/[[Macross]]). 

According to the creator of the comic many foreign comic artists and authors -who published their works monthly - couldn't believe that a weekly comic was even possible at the time of publication of [i]Karmatron[/i].

The "ancient astronaut theory":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_astronaut_theory is one of the principal components of the main storyline in Karmatron. [[Buddhism]], [[Taoism]], "Esoterism":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_esotericism and "Mayanism":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mayanism are also featured heavily in the series.

title: three-nine_(space_train)
body:
The eponymous fictional space craft of the [[Ginga Tetsudou 999]] [[science fiction]] series from the [[1970s_(style)|70s]] created by [[Matsumoto Leiji]].

The [b]Special Limited Express Three-Nine[/b] (銀河超特急 999号) is actually a very advanced and sophisticated long range interstellar transport [[spacecraft]]. It is shaped like an old steam [[train]] so its passengers are more comfortable and feel more at home, becoming less nostalgic of [[earth_(planet)|Earth]] as the ship travels to planets and places located very far away in the far reaches of the [[Milky Way]] galaxy.

It is operated by an [[alien]] called [[Conductor_(ginga_tetsudou_999)|]].

The basic design is based in a [[Japan]]ese National Railways Steam Locomotive "C-62":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JNR_Class_C62] Model.

title: treasure_island
body:
[b]Treasure Island[/b] is an adventure novel by Scottish author Robert Louis Stevenson, narrating a tale of "buccaneers and buried [[gold]]". First published as a book on May 23, 1883, it was originally serialized in the children's magazine [i]Young Folks[/i] between 1881–82 under the title "Treasure Island or, the mutiny of the Hispaniola" with Stevenson adopting the pseudonym Captain George North and [[Jim Hawkins]] as the main character in the story.

Traditionally considered a "coming of age" story, Treasure Island is an adventure tale known for its atmosphere, characters and action, and also as a wry commentary on the ambiguity of morality [spoilers](as seen in the character [[Long John Silver]])[/spoilers] unusual for children's literature now and then. 

It is one of the most frequently dramatized of all novels. The influence of Treasure Island on popular perceptions of [[pirate]]s is enormous, including [[treasure]] [[map]]s marked with an "X", schooners, the "Black Spot", tropical [[island]]s, and one-legged seamen carrying [[parrot]]s on their shoulders. It is also well-renowned for its many adaptations in different media, whether it be the 1950 Walt Disney film, the 1978 Japanese anime [[Takarajima]], the [[treasure island (1988)|1988 Soviet animated film]], the 1996 movie Muppet Treasure Island, or 2002's [[Treasure Planet]]. 

h4. See also

For the first 3 years of production, this model of the Skyline was nearly identical to it's Infiniti counterpart (the only difference being the name), even sporting Infiniti badges despite the brand not being offered in the Japanese market. body:
The [b]Tachikawa Ki-36 Type 98 Army Co-operation Aircraft[/b] was an [[Imperial Japanese Army]] multirole recon-close air support-ground attack aircraft from [[World War II]].

Originally seeing use as a ground attack aircraft in China, it was later pressed into service as kamikaze craft late-war.

title: yokosuka_r2y2
body:
The [b]Yokosuka R2Y Keiun[/b] was an [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] reconnaissance aircraft from the later years of [[World War II]]. 

The [i]Keiun[/i] came in two variants: a tandem-engine and six-bladed propeller-powered recon craft (R2Y1), and a light [[bomber]] powered by two [[jet engine]]s (R2Y2), none of which ever entered production.

title: b5m
body:
The [b]Mitsubishi B5M[/b] (Type 97 No. 2) was an [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] torpedo bomber developed and introduced in 1937 for carrier use. Seeing service at the same time as Nakajima's own [[B5N]] (both were designed to meet a 1935 Navy requirement for a long-range monoplane torpedo bomber), it lost out to the B5N as the standard carrier-based torpedo bomber of the IJN at the start of the war.

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia: Mitsubishi B5M":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitsubishi_B5M]

title: diamond_plate
body: Diamond plate, also known as checker plate or tread plate, is a metal plate with diamond-shaped textures on it as anti-slip feature. Due to ease of production combined with lower hazard risk, diamond plates are commonly used as flooring for [[contemporary]] structures such as [[factory]], [[bridge]]s or [[stairs]].

title: bristol_beaufighter
body:
The [b]Bristol Type 156 Beaufighter[/b] was a British [[World War II]] twin engine heavy fighter. A fighter development of the earlier Beaufort, it was used for a number of roles including night-fighter, [[torpedo bomber]] (Torbeau), and rocket-armed ground attack aircraft (Rockbeau). It was also used as an improvised maritime strike aircraft and anti-shipping aircraft (as in the battle of the Bismarck Sea, post #4403886).

It was predominantly used by Commonwealth air forces, especially [[Australia]], that even produced its own Beaufighters domestically.

h4.See also

* [[List of Airplanes]]

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Bristol Beaufighter":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bristol_Beaufighter]

title: ohajiki
body:
Ohajiki (おはじき?) is a traditional Japanese children's game similar to marbles. It is played with small coin-shaped pieces also called ohajiki. The pieces are typically made of glass or plastic, although historically the game was often played with pebbles or go stones. The game became popular as an indoor game for girls during the Edo period. (from Wikipedia)

Ohajiki at Wikipedia: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ohajiki

title: d4y_suisei
body:
The [b]Yokosuka D4Y Suisei[/b] (彗星, "Comet", Allied nickname "Judy") was an [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] [[dive bomber]], built to replace the older Aichi [[D3A]] Type 99.

While it was designed from the onset as a dive bomber, the first examples flew in the [[battle of Midway]] as a reconnaissance craft due to some flaws until it was corrected and cleared for dive bombing. Its high speed also made it valuable as an improvised interceptor with an upward-mounted cannon (post #4449223), but it shared the same fragility as [[A6M Zero|other]] [[G4M|planes]] of their time.

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia: Yokosuka D4Y":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yokosuka_D4Y]

title: a_bathing_ape
body:
A Japanese [[streetwear]] brand founded by Teriyaki Boyz member Nigo in 1993, opening a store named NOWHERE alongside fellow designer Jun Takahashi of Undercover. Popularized in the US by [[Kanye West]] in the early 2000s, the brand is most well known for it's [[shark hood|shark hoodies]], original [[camouflage|camo]] patterns, and their [[Baby Milo]] mascot. They have a more affordable offshoot brand in AAPE, and have had crossovers with numerous well known franchises including [[Naruto]], [[One Piece]], [[Dragon Ball]], [[Gundam]], [[Transformers]], [[Star Wars]], and the [[Ultra series]], as well as many official collaborations with American rappers.

The brand was sold to Hong Kong fashion business conglomerate I.T Group in 2011. Nigo remained at the brand for 2 years before departing in 2013.

Informally known as BAPE.

title: sdf-1
body:
A legendary, massive, fictional variable [[spacecraft]] from the [[MACROSS]] [[science fiction]] anime series. 

The [b]U.N. Spacy SDF-1 (Super Dimensional Fortress One) "Macross"[/b] is the titular [[space]] fortress (and [[mecha]]) from the anime [[Choujikuu Yousai Macross]] released in the 80s. 

This massive [[alien]] [[spacecraft]] was originally [spoilers]a [[Supervision Army]] Gun Destroyer that crashlanded in [[South Ataria]] island on Earth in the year 1999 (codenamed [[ASS-1]] or [b]Alien Space Ship One[/b] by U.N. Spacy scientists),[/spoilers] but was later repaired and reconstructed, thus becoming humanity's main defense against the [[Zentradi]].

The SDF-1 is 1.2 km long and can transform from Cruiser into [[Storm Attacker]] mode. It is equipped with a "Fold" drive that enables the ship to travel through [i]Super Dimension[/i] space (or [i]Hyperspace[/i]), thus making it capable of traveling several light years between different star systems in a matter of hours.

The Macross is armed with a very powerful "Super-Dimension" (hyperspace) energy cannon with a beam polarizing converging system, as well as several energy cannons, electro-magnetic rail cannons and anti-ship [[missile]] launchers. 

The ship also has several [[QF-3000E]] [[Ghost drone]] fighters, [[VF-1]] variable fighters and many [[Tomahawk (Destroid)|Tomahawk]], [[Defender (macross)|]], [[Spartan (Destroid)|Spartan]], [[phalanx (Destroid)|Phalanx]] and [[Monster Destroid|Monster]] [[Destroid]] [[mecha]] on its multiple hangar bays.

In [[real life]] the SDF-1 was designed by [[Miyatake Kazutaka]] in the early 80s. The design was inspired by the [[yamato_(uchuu_senkan_yamato)|Yamato]] from [[Uchuu Senkan Yamato]] and the [[White Base]] from [[Mobile Suit Gundam]].

title: steyr_iws_2000
body:
An Austrian single-shot [[bolt action]] [[anti-materiel rifle]] produced by Steyr Mannlicher, designed in mid-1980s. [b]IWS[/b] stands for Infantry Weapon System. Like many anti-tank rifles, it is actually a smoothbore weapon. This can help accelerate projectiles and increase ballistic effectiveness, but the lack of rifling imparting inertial stability requires the projectile to have stabilizing fins. It is chambered in a 15.2×169 mm armor-piercing fin-stabilized discarding-sabot [[ammunition|cartridge]], and is the first man-portable rifle to use this type of ammunition.

title: pc-98_(computer)
body:
Formally the [b]NEC PC-9801[/b], a line of Japanese 16-bit and 32-bit [[computer|personal computers]] made by NEC from 1982 to 2000.

Despite having inferior hardware to the Fujitsu FM Towns and Sharp [[X68000]] PCs, it was popular among the Japanese for its steady flow of games, such as “dōjin” style dating sims and RPGs. In the West, it is perhaps best known as the platform on which the earliest [i][[Touhou]][/i] games were released.

This tag is for depictions of the computer itself. For images in the style of the PC-98's graphics, see the [[PC-98 (style)]] tag.

title: rabbit_day
body:
Rabbit Day is a [[date pun]] that happens on March 3rd. Its origin comes from goroawase: 3-3 can be read as "mi-mi" which can mean "ear".
It can be called Ears Day for all the animals, but because rabbits have long ears, it gradually became a day dedicated to rabbits.

Don't confuse with [[Bunny Day]] which is a date pun related to [[playboy bunny]].
